</aside><p>You can also think of phi as a number that can be squared by add=
ing one to that number itself, according to an explainer from mathematician=
 <a data-analytics-id=3D"inline-link" href=3D"http://www.maths.surrey.ac.uk=
/hosted-sites/R.Knott/Fibonacci/phi.html" data-url=3D"http://www.maths.surr=
ey.ac.uk/hosted-sites/R.Knott/Fibonacci/phi.html" target=3D"_blank" referre=
rpolicy=3D"no-referrer-when-downgrade" data-hl-processed=3D"none" data-mrf-=
recirculation=3D"inline-link" data-mrf-link=3D"http://www.maths.surrey.ac.u=
k/hosted-sites/R.Knott/Fibonacci/phi.html" cmp-ltrk=3D"inline-link" cmp-ltr=
k-idx=3D"2" mrfobservableid=3D"ba62bcf6-a647-46b4-bd29-5b75ea4630d2" data-h=
awk-tracked=3D"hawklinks"><u>Ron Knott</u></a> at the University of Surrey =
in the U.K. So, phi can be expressed this way:</p><div id=3D"ad-unit-2" cla=
ss=3D"ad-unit"></div><p>phi^2 =3D phi + 1</p><p>This representation can be =
rearranged into a <a data-analytics-id=3D"inline-link" href=3D"https://www.=
livescience.com/50411-quadratic-equations.html" data-mrf-recirculation=3D"i=
nline-link" data-before-rewrite-localise=3D"https://www.livescience.com/504=
11-quadratic-equations.html" data-mrf-link=3D"https://www.livescience.com/5=
