gcaption></figure><p id=3D"57ba85a5-d9a9-431e-9b85-d6e6b4cbfb1a">But as Mar=
kowsky pointed out in his 1992 paper in the <a data-analytics-id=3D"inline-=
link" href=3D"https://www.goldennumber.net/wp-content/uploads/George-Markow=
sky-Golden-Ratio-Misconceptions-MAA.pdf" data-url=3D"https://www.goldennumb=
er.net/wp-content/uploads/George-Markowsky-Golden-Ratio-Misconceptions-MAA.=
pdf" target=3D"_blank" referrerpolicy=3D"no-referrer-when-downgrade" data-h=
l-processed=3D"none" data-mrf-recirculation=3D"inline-link" data-mrf-link=
=3D"https://www.goldennumber.net/wp-content/uploads/George-Markowsky-Golden=
-Ratio-Misconceptions-MAA.pdf" cmp-ltrk=3D"inline-link" cmp-ltrk-idx=3D"8" =
mrfobservableid=3D"48563957-7c6b-46b0-babb-d445ec86837b" data-hawk-tracked=
=3D"hawklinks"><u>College Mathematics Journal</u></a>, titled "Misconceptio=
ns About the Golden Ratio": "measurements of real objects can only be appro=
ximations. Surfaces of real objects are never perfectly flat." He went on t=
o write that inaccuracies in the precision of measurements lead to greater =
inaccuracies when those measurements are put into ratios, so claims about a=
ncient buildings or art conforming to phi should be taken with a heavy grai=
n of salt.&nbsp;</p><p>The dimensions of architectural masterpieces are oft=
en said to be close to phi, but as Markowsky discussed, sometimes this mean=
s that people simply look for a ratio that yields 1.6 and call that phi. Fi=
nding two segments whose ratio is 1.6 is not particularly difficult. Where =
one chooses to measure from can be arbitrary and adjusted if necessary to g=
et the values closer to phi.</p><p>Attempts to find phi in the human body a=
lso succumb to similar fallacies. A recent study claimed to find the golden=
 ratio in different proportions of the human skull. But as Dale Ritter, the=
 lead human anatomy instructor for Alpert Medical School (AMS) at Brown Uni=
versity in Rhode Island, <a data-analytics-id=3D"inline-link" href=3D"https=
://www.livescience.com/golden-ratio-human-skull.html" data-mrf-recirculatio=
n=3D"inline-link" data-before-rewrite-localise=3D"https://www.livescience.c=
om/golden-ratio-human-skull.html" data-mrf-link=3D"https://www.livescience.=
com/golden-ratio-human-skull.html" cmp-ltrk=3D"inline-link" cmp-ltrk-idx=3D=
"9" mrfobservableid=3D"4fd0ca09-86fa-46d2-9f59-9188415ee36b" data-url=3D"ht=
tps://www.livescience.com/golden-ratio-human-skull.html" data-hl-processed=
=3D"none" data-hawk-tracked=3D"hawklinks"><u>told Live Science</u></a>:&nbs=
p;</p><p>"I believe the overarching problem with this paper is that there i=
s very little (perhaps no) science in it =E2=80=A6 with so many bones and s=
o many points of interest on those bones, I'd imagine there would be at lea=
st a few" golden ratios elsewhere in the&nbsp;<a data-analytics-id=3D"inlin=
e-link" href=3D"https://www.livescience.com/22537-skeletal-system.html" dat=
a-mrf-recirculation=3D"inline-link" data-before-rewrite-localise=3D"https:/=
/www.livescience.com/22537-skeletal-system.html" data-mrf-link=3D"https://w=
ww.livescience.com/22537-skeletal-system.html" cmp-ltrk=3D"inline-link" cmp=
-ltrk-idx=3D"10" mrfobservableid=3D"431222e3-32eb-4810-8c4f-c03fff7770da" d=
ata-url=3D"https://www.livescience.com/22537-skeletal-system.html" data-hl-=
processed=3D"none" data-hawk-tracked=3D"hawklinks"><u>human skeletal system=
</u></a>.&nbsp;</p><p><strong>Related: </strong><a data-analytics-id=3D"inl=
ine-link" href=3D"https://www.livescience.com/63429-big-numbers-universe-ph=
otos.html" data-mrf-recirculation=3D"inline-link" data-before-rewrite-local=
ise=3D"https://www.livescience.com/63429-big-numbers-universe-photos.html" =
data-mrf-link=3D"https://www.livescience.com/63429-big-numbers-universe-pho=
tos.html" cmp-ltrk=3D"inline-link" cmp-ltrk-idx=3D"11" mrfobservableid=3D"2=
06e5eda-695a-4055-90c9-2d0bff64c45b" data-url=3D"https://www.livescience.co=
m/63429-big-numbers-universe-photos.html" data-hl-processed=3D"none" data-h=
awk-tracked=3D"hawklinks"><strong>Photos: Large Numbers That Define the Uni=
verse</strong></a></p><p>And while phi is said to be common in nature, its =
significance is overblown. Flower petals often come in Fibonacci numbers, s=
uch as five or eight, and pine cones grow their seeds outward in spirals of=
 Fibonacci numbers. But there are just as many plants that don't follow thi=
s rule as those that do, Keith Devlin, a mathematician at Stanford Universi=
ty, <a data-analytics-id=3D"inline-link" href=3D"https://www.livescience.co=
m/37470-fibonacci-sequence.html" data-mrf-recirculation=3D"inline-link" dat=
a-before-rewrite-localise=3D"https://www.livescience.com/37470-fibonacci-se=
quence.html" data-mrf-link=3D"https://www.livescience.com/37470-fibonacci-s=
equence.html" cmp-ltrk=3D"inline-link" cmp-ltrk-idx=3D"12" mrfobservableid=
=3D"f8ff4413-9599-4b0a-8865-72c56a838336" data-url=3D"https://www.livescien=
ce.com/37470-fibonacci-sequence.html" data-hl-processed=3D"none" data-hawk-=
tracked=3D"hawklinks"><u>told Live Science</u></a>.</p><p>People have claim=
ed that seashells, such as those of the nautilus, exhibit properties in whi=
ch phi lurks. But as Devlin <a data-analytics-id=3D"inline-link" href=3D"ht=
tps://www.maa.org/external_archive/devlin/devlin_05_07.html" data-url=3D"ht=
tps://www.maa.org/external_archive/devlin/devlin_05_07.html" target=3D"_bla=
nk" referrerpolicy=3D"no-referrer-when-downgrade" data-hl-processed=3D"none=
" data-mrf-recirculation=3D"inline-link" data-mrf-link=3D"https://www.maa.o=
rg/external_archive/devlin/devlin_05_07.html" cmp-ltrk=3D"inline-link" cmp-=
ltrk-idx=3D"13" mrfobservableid=3D"69e5bbf5-3c57-4d15-b54c-fce0c9b06b25" da=
ta-hawk-tracked=3D"hawklinks"><u>points out on his website</u></a>, "the na=
utilus does grow its shell in a fashion that follows a logarithmic spiral, =
i.e., spiral that turns by a constant angle along its entire length, making=
 it everywhere self-similar. But that constant angle is not the golden rati=
o. Pity, I know, but there it is."</p><p>While phi is certainly an interest=
ing mathematical idea, it is we humans who assign importance to things we f=
ind in the universe. An advocate looking through phi-colored glasses might =
see the golden ratio everywhere. But it's always useful to step outside a p=
articular perspective and ask whether the world truly conforms to our limit=
ed understanding of it.&nbsp;</p><p><strong>Additional resources:&nbsp;</st=
rong></p><ul id=3D"26fbffd2-da68-4697-9101-4e4ff0a2a73f"><li>Here's a helpf=
